Reaction to earnings

Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research

Q2 beat & upside to Street's Q3/FY26 expectations were better than expected across the board. Modest upward revision to margin shows commitment to expansion with signs of continued productivity improvements. Initial FY29 operating margin target of 41% (as reported) another positive. Remain OW.

Ex FX & transaction model, Q2 revenue growth of 11% reflected durability from Q1 while billings accelerated to 26% from 22% YoY and OPM increased 2pts QoQ FY26 targets increased across the board (incl. FCF & EPS up 4% & 3%, respectively) as 1H momentum flowed through, while mgmt remains prudent in 2H outlook... ...Which includes slightly tougher comps, especially in Q4, as ADSK laps acquisition impacts (~1pt of growth) & new transaction model impacts from last year Q2 results build confidence in the margin expansion to new FY29 targets (41% as reported, 45% underlying) given continued execution & productivity improvements Shares trading \(\geq 15\%\) discount to peers plus a catalyst path for improved demand, margin and investor sentiment frames a favorable risk/reward; remain OW

Staying Focused. Autodesk delivered clean Q2 results with impressive upside across revenue (+2% versus consensus, up from average \(\sim 100\) bps in recent quarters), billings (+8% vs Street), operating income (+5%) and FCF. FQ3/FY26 guidance also impressed with raises across the board as momentum in 1H is flowed through. Excluding FX and transaction model ('core'), FY26 revenue and billings targets impacts each increased \(\sim 1\) pt to 9- 10% YoY and 17- 19% YoY, respectively, while operating margin was raised to the high- end of prior guide ( \(\sim 40\%\) ) and reported FCF/EPS targets increased \(\sim 4\% / \sim 3\%\) . Alongside improving execution, management is

remaining prudent in 2H guidance which continues to embed covid- like headwinds due to tariffs at the low- end. While management acknowledged tougher comps in 2H, largely due to lapping acquisition impacts (\\~1pt of growth) and new transaction model impacts from last year, we are encouraged by the improving execution, which sets up well into FY27 and beyond. Q2 highlighted improving partner efficiency with value- add partners seeing an uptick in new business, as management spoke to a "stair- like" improvement pattern on new business growth which should continue in 2H. Autodesk also saw strength in its e- store in Q2 as well, as business from low- end partners is moving over to the e- store as part of the new transaction model, driving better margins given the lack of a commissions component. Longer- term, management provided an early view into a FY29 GAAP operating margin target of \(41\%\) (as reported) and \(45\%\) underlying (ex- transaction model). We expect more color to be shared at the upcoming analyst day on 10/7. Bottom line, bigger Q2 beat and steady positive revisions to FY26 reflect execution over the near- term which builds credibility to achieving the long- term margin targets. We walk away more constructive on EPS and FCF generation supported by stable topline and margin expansion, which is not priced into shares trading at 26x EV/FCF and 1.0x growth- adjusted, a discount to large- cap software at 34x and 1.8x. Reiterate OW.

- Strong Beats Across the Board in Q2. Autodesk posted a strong Q2 print, beating consensus expectations by a higher magnitude than usual, supported by strong underlying momentum and limited macro impacts thus far. Reported revenue reached \$1.8B in the quarter, growing 17% YoY, and beat consensus expectations by >2%, while billings grew 36% YoY to -\(1.7B and came in 8% above Street's expectations. On the back of a stronger topline performance, Q2 operating margin of \~39% beat expectations by 92bps and drove EPS of \$2.62 to come in 18c above estimates. FCF margin also impressed at 26%, above expectations calling for \~13% margin.

- Color on Long-Term Margin Expansion... With More Coming at Upcoming A-Day and Autodesk University. As Autodesk remains focused on delivering "GAAP margins among the best in the industry," management provided initial color on longer-term operating margins to reach \~41% in FY29 on an as reported basis (Q1: 45% ex transaction model impacts), which came in roughly 1pt above prior consensus expectations. Management mentioned that the path between now and FY29 for margin expansion may not be linear given incremental margin headwinds from the new transaction model next year. Management also mentioned that operating income and FCF should be highly correlated going forward once the overall business model settles and the new transaction model takes hold. We expect Autodesk to provide additional color on the long-term path for operating margin expansion, as well as underlying business model changes (though unlikely to provide topline growth targets) at the upcoming analyst day on October 7. At Autodesk University, we expect to get more color on new product announcements across the broader platform as well as the latest AI innovations within the Autodesk portfolio.
- Strong Underlying Execution Supported by AEC and Construction Businesses. Autodesk's Architecture, Engineering, and Construction (AEC)

segment saw particular strength in the quarter, with \(23\%\) YoY growth accelerating from \(20\%\) last quarter to \(50\%\) of total revenue. Management noted that AEC benefitted from continued strong investments in data centers, industrial buildings, and infrastructure, which helped offset some softness in commercial end- markets. On the construction side, Autodesk noted particularly strong revenue growth in the quarter from existing customers as well as solid momentum with net new customers. The overall strength in construction has remained consistent over the past few quarters as win rates in the US at both the top of the pyramid and the mid- market remain strong, while new adds internationally has also seen sustained traction.

- Tougher Comps Ahead. Despite the typical large EBA renewals in the back half of this year, Autodesk noted some potentially tougher comps, particularly in Q4. Specifically, management pointed to acquisition impacts (\~1pt of growth) and new transaction model impacts from last year, which the company will be lapping in F2H26. 
- Macro Assumptions Remain Consistent. Autodesk has not seen major macro impacts as of today, yet remains fairly cautious with underlying macro assumptions baked into the forward guidance given continued macro uncertainty. To that end, management noted, "The underlying momentum of business in the 2026 was consistent with recent quarters, and better than the more cautious assumptions built into the bottom end of our prior guidance range. The macroeconomic environment seems broadly stable but uncertainty remains elevated." With that said, Autodesk has not seen any major tariff impacts, yet the low-end of guidance still assumes covid-like headwinds to new business growth and EBA renewals. 
- Transformational M&A Unlikely. Regarding headlines about PTC (see Would Autodesk Acquire PTC? (10 Jul 2025)), management mentioned that they remain focused on further investments for driving organic growth revolved around the platform strategy and AI products, as well as tuck-in acquisitions to drive platform expansion. Management characterized tuck-in acquisitions "tend to be in the hundreds of thousands to the billions of dollars range, not in the tens of billions of dollars range" - thus muting likelihood of transformational deals. Autodesk also remains focused on returning capital to shareholders through share buybacks, which continued in the quarter.

Price Target Change: PT Increase to \(385 From\) 370. \(385 is based on 33x EV/ FCF FY27e FCF/share of\) 11.83. A slightly higher PT is warranted in our view given impressive Q2 results and Q2/FY26 guidance driven by continued strong momentum across the Autodesk platform and stable underlying demand, coupled with peer multiple expansion.
